node.text:
657 Highland Ave, Fall River, MA 02720
$1,200,000, 6 bd, 3 ba, 4,577 sqft

Located in the Highlands, The Rising Sun,  An innovative Japanese-influenced residential design by Ralph Adams Cram, an INFLUENCER of Frank Lloyd Wright.  Cram’s design of the Rising Sun is a seminal Japanese Arts and Crafts house listed on the Massachusetts Historic Register. Situated on a ½ acre,  this uniquely charming home was built in 1894 with exacting attention to detail. This notable historic house has many features as well as future possibilities.  Beamed ceilings, beautiful woodwork, a skylighted central staircase, 4 working fireplaces, home offices on both the 2nd and 3rd floors, as well as 6 bedrooms . Hardwood floors throughout the home, a Japanese teahouse, and signed carved wooden panels, are just a few of the features of this intriguing home.  Constructed by the  Japanese technique  known as KANAWA TSUGI which doesn't use nails but bonds wood to wood.  It is built so well that the original solid Walnut doors still exist over 127 years.

Listed by:
David Durot
Century 21 Topsail Realty - Newport

node.text:
301 Main Street, Oxford Alabama, 36203
$274,900, 6 bd, 5 ba, 5,271 sqft

This downtown Oxford home will captivate you with its beauty and history. As one of the only properties in Alabama listed on the national historic registry, its charm and character has been preserved over the last century. As you walk through the home you will visualize the narrative told about the life of a family at the turn of the century. Included in these features is the genuine copper fountain and basin used by Annie Cooper to water her ferns, the original kitchen with authentic 1800's appliances and components and bathrooms with cast iron claw foot tub and fixtures installed at the origin of indoor plumbing. In addition to the house the property contains three other historic resources. A recreational building to the rear of the house contains a rare box ball alley, a precursor to a modern bowling alley, the only one known of in the state of Alabama, a gazebo built in the early 1900's constructed from the branches of trees and a brick garage.

Listed By:
Karl Heckman
eXp Realty, LLC Central

Christie Heckman

1700 S Louisiana St, Little Rock, AR 72206
$549,900, 4 bd, 4 ba, 4,468 sqft

Meticulously restored historic home! The Turner-Ledbetter House is a two-story, 4BR/3.5BA Queen Anne style Victorian home full of original detail and elegant finishes. Gorgeous woodwork, fireplace mantels and hardwood flooring. Wonderful kitchen features an island and a double oven. Fabulous sun porch and much more! Situated on a double lot, the grounds have been lovingly maintained and manicured. There is also a 1400sf carriage house w/2BR/2BA and a living area. National Register of Historic Places 1987.
FIREPLACE

Blairsden is a historic 62,000 square foot, 38-room mansion located in Peapack-Gladstone, New Jersey. Set high on a hilltop overlooking Ravine Lake, the mansion is part of what was originally an estate of 550 acres. In addition to its 38 rooms, the mansion has 25 fireplaces and 19 bathrooms. Photo by @thegildedbutler

node.text:
Chetstone House, built in 1876, in New Haven, CT, the Victorian Gothic house was one of three show pieces that graced the highest ridge of Fair Haven Heights . The house was built by Dr. Mary Blair Moody, the first female to practice medicine in the New Haven area. In 1915, the house’s second owner, Albert Haasis, a chemist and executive of the Dixon Pencil Company named the house “Chetstone.” Passionate about art and horticulture, he kept lavish gardens replete with peacocks and filled the house with artwork, including an attic full of whimsical rabbit paintings, reminiscent of Alice in Wonderland. In its 138-year history, Chetstone has only had five owners and as a result has retained its architectural integrity and excellence: from its brownstone foundation and cistern pump in the cellar, to original trim, moldings, doors and working gas lamps throughout. Photo from their website. @chetstone_nhv

node.text:
197 Ruggles Avenue, Newport, RI 02840
29 BEDS, 7.64 ACRES, 18 BATHS, 1 1/2 BATHS, 43,772 SQFT

Historic "Seaview Terrace" is perched atop nearly eight acres of seaside property along Newport's famed Cliff Walk. At over 43,000 square feet, Seaview is the fifth largest estate in Newport and the largest that remains privately owned. Built in 1907 for Edson Bradley, it was originally located in Dupont Circle in Washington, D.C. The home covered more than half a city block, and included a chapel with seating for 150, a large ballroom, an art gallery, and a 500-seat theatre. In 1923, Bradley began disassembling his Washington, D.C. mansion and relocating it to Newport. "Sea View", the Elizabethan-Revival mansion already on the site, was incorporated into the design, and lent its name to the new chateau. Rooms that had been imported intact from France and installed in Washington, D.C. twenty years earlier were moved again and reassembled in Newport, and the new building was constructed around them. The ALA awarded Bradley's architect, Howard Greenley, the 1928 President's Medal for the chateau. Seaview boasts many articles of virtu including "The Flagellation" (circa 154447) an early-Renaissance stained-glass window designed for Milan Cathedral. The Great Hall features a whispering gallery, an elliptical room reminiscent of Saint Paul's Cathedral, in which a person standing at one of the foci can hear the slightest whisper uttered at the other. Long used as a dormitory, this is a once in a lifetime opportunity to restore and preserve a true piece of history.

Listed By:
Hawks and Company
Office: 401.783.1007
